    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-01-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-01-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="443"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d443">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 341.115Am319/104</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-01-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 3, 1916</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received 2.50 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3493. Your 2603, December 20, and 2645 and 2646, 29, re <hi rend="italic"
                        >Kankakee</hi>.<note n="1" xml:id="d443fn1">Nos. 2603 and 2645 not
                        printed</note> Foreign Office informs me that it is now in receipt of
                    communication from Admiralty from which it appears that this vessel was captured
                    by British naval forces as far back as October 31 last, and that she has been
                    conveyed to Gibraltar where she is at present on the point of arrival.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Embassy</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
